If so, subtract 1 from the result. So translating the loops:

Original Java code:

for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    for (int k = i + 1; k <= n; k++) {
        if ((i + k) % 2 == 0) {
            int j = (i + k) / 2;
            char is = s.charAt(i-1);
            char ks = s.charAt(k-1);
            char js = s.charAt(j-1);
            if (is != ks && ks ! = js && js ! = is) {
                result--;
            }
        }
    }
} In Fortran, since the string is 1-based, the i and k loop variables can directly index into s. So when i is 1 in Fortran, s(i) is the first character, which matches the Java code's i-1 when i starts at 1. So the Fortran loops would be:

do i=1, n
    do k = i+1, n
        if (mod(i + k, 2) == 0 then
            j = (i + k) / 2
            if (s(i:i) /= s(k:k) .and. s(k:k) /= s(j:j) .and. s(j:j) /= s(i:i)) then
                result = result - 1
            endif
        endif
    end do
end do

But wait, j has to be between i and k. Since k is i+1 and beyond, and j is (i +k)/2. For example, if i=1, k=3, then j=2. So yes, j is between i and k. So that's correct.
